00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:43.560
Today we are delighted
to host this panel

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:47.660
in the Knafel Center, a place
with a distinctly athletic

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:48.850
history.

00:02:48.850 --> 00:02:53.360
Until 1977, this
building was a gymnasium

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:55.880
for the women of
Radcliffe College.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:00.020
Students ran laps around the
track that's above our heads.

00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:02.610
They climbed ropes,
and you can see

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:06.620
some of the scars of much
of the gym equipment.

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:09.010
And they formed their
own basketball team

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:12.230
starting in 1895,
long before they

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:14.990
had access to the
leagues, the uniforms,

00:03:14.990 --> 00:03:19.360
and the other resources that
Harvard men took for granted.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.200
Certainly, much has changed.

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:25.410
But damaging social
attitudes persist,

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:28.820
and not just among the members
of the Harvard men's soccer

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:29.700
team.

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:34.250
Female competitors continue to
exercise their athletic talents

00:03:34.250 --> 00:03:37.980
to less acclaim and for
smaller financial rewards

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:40.760
than their male counterparts do.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:44.090
Advertising provides
a revealing window

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:46.740
into these stubborn prejudices.

00:03:46.740 --> 00:03:50.580
Take for instance, one of
the most enduring and iconic

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:53.730
examples of sports marketing.

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:58.400
Wheaties has been featuring
athletes on their cereal boxes

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:01.120
since 1934.

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:06.040
In the very first year of this
now classic marketing strategy,

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.660
a woman did appear on the box.

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:13.210
She was Eleanor Smith, a pilot,
who remains the only person

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:17.450
to have flown a plane under all
four bridges of New York's East

00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:19.190
River.

00:04:19.190 --> 00:04:23.260
Unfortunately, Smith
turned out to be an outlier

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:25.420
in more ways than one.

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:28.540
It would be 50 years
before Wheaties

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:30.560
featured another woman.

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:33.780
In 1984, and many of
you will remember this,

00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:36.080
when Olympic gymnast,
Mary Lou Retton,

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:39.170
appeared on the
familiar orange box,

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:42.090
children could finally
see a celebration

00:04:42.090 --> 00:04:46.790
of female athleticism as they
ate their breakfast cereal.

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:49.960
Three decades later, I'm
glad to say that women

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:52.790
do appear on Wheaties boxes.

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:57.390
And two women have even made
it onto Forbes magazine's list

00:04:57.390 --> 00:04:59.870
of the highest paid athletes.

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:04.010
But female athletes
continue to face disparities

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:08.690
in pay, in endorsement
deals, and in media coverage.

00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:14.140
In 2014, only 2% of
Sports Center air time

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:16.380
covered women's sports.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:20.030
And a recent lawsuit by
the US women's soccer team

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:22.320
revealed that some
professional male soccer

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.970
players are paid four times more
than their female counterparts.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:31.300
The multi-faceted issue
of women in sports

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:34.230
is best addressed from
multiple perspectives, which

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:36.600
is why we have brought
together this very

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:39.070
fine group of panelists today.

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:40.660
